{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CdHDgPdzw16o5MYBnPzH4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 3 tests pass. Fixed.\n\n**Root cause:** In `src/validate.js`, the domain regex was `[A-Za-z0-9-]+(\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]*)*\\.[A-Za-z]{2,}`. The inner label used `*` (zero-or-more), so a dot followed by an *empty* label was legal — that's exactly what `..` is. So `user@mail..example.com` matched `mail` + `.`(empty label) + `.example` + `.com`. The code's own comment said \"Labels must be NON-EMPTY,\" so the `*` contradicted the intended spec.\n\n**Fix:** Changed the inner quantifier from `*` to `+`, requiring each label between dots to have at least one character:\n\n```\n/^[^\\s@]+@[A-Za-z0-9-]+(\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]+)*\\.[A-Za-z]{2,}$/\n```\n\nConsecutive dots (and by extension `mail..`) now fail; valid addresses like `ada@example.com` still pass. I added a regression test that reproduced the bounce before the fix and passes after it."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":233,"cache_read_input_tokens":29072,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":233},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae80d891-78a1-4070-8352-b5efba356e41","uuid":"132f3b2e-42d0-415e-a129-afb7207b9f0f","timestamp":"2026-07-22T14:02:22.454Z","request_id":"req_011CdHDgLM4XgpenMy8hJhpw"}
